item.title: Quest tab
item.dc:creator: @tyb97 tyb97
item.description:
@tyb97 wrote:

[quote=".:, post:12, topic:464536"][quote author=tyb97 link=topic=568572.msg4127383#msg4127383 date=1350612634]
In the interface editor, you could do something like
“Player Name:” + “X”

THEN send the player’s name server sided to the id for X. This way, for one, it won’t say “View Quest” when you hover over “Player Name:” or “Tyb97”, it won’t say anything. Lastly, it won’t have to loop through and change itself EVERYTIME the player logs it, which is just plain efficient, common sense, and good practice. It gives the interface a nice clean look and feel, not like a children’s coloring book.
[/quote]

Your right, lets waste time sending the name to the client when the players name is already represented in the client. And if you took the time to actually work it out instead of just slapping it into the initialization methods, it wouldn’t look like a ‘child’s’ coloring book.[/quote]
Actually, since the interfaces are in the cache, and all the client code isn’t renamed correctly, you could have a lot of fun doing that. You don’t have to slap it all into the initialization methods, but whatever the hell methods that carry out this task, are still called in these methods, so your argument is invalid.

item.title: Quest tab
item.dc:creator: @ExtremeX-Scape Ryley
item.description:
@ExtremeX-Scape wrote:

[quote=".:, post:7, topic:464536"][quote author=tyb97 link=topic=568572.msg4127374#msg4127374 date=1350611826]

If your interfaces are packed, use an interface editor.

There’s already a a outgoing packet for writing over text.

sendFrame126(String, Integer); for project insanity.

That packet works for any 317 client. An interface editor would be the right way to go, for many reasons. One being that the underlying buttons are still there, you just can’t see the text. Looping through all those lines of text on player initialization takes serious toll on speeds, and for it to look right he would have to replace EVERY line of text.
[/quote]

Replacing 10 - 50 lines of text would not require an interface editor in any way. And it would take less then 3 second of start up time to write those lines.[/quote]

Why would you write over the current String when you can replace it client sided?

That is one of the most idiotic things I’ve read.

Also, sendString(string, interfaceId, subInterfaceId) doesn’t replace all occurrences of the String, and, I have only seen one server that has used the sendString method correctly implementing the subInterfaceId as well.

Read full topic
